 name="root" value="ns:ncrx"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001003-20180326-161854"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipc">N/CRM N/GEN N/LEN R/CA R/NME R/US R/USW </DescField><DescField fid="ipd">WSJ WSJ.com WSJ.com Site Search WSJAsia WSJEurope WSJ Japanese Online WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com WSJSunday POLICE KILLINGS POLICE SHOOTINGS SACRAMENTO DEMONSTRATIONS SACRAMENTO POLICE PROTESTS SACRAMENTO POLICE SHOOTING SACRAMENTO PROTESTS STEPHON CLARK SB123055822488121348798045841259914456786981 Brown, Michael Clark, Stephon Cousins, DeMarcus Crump, Benjamin Davis, Timothy Steinberg, Darrell Thompson, Sequita SYND CODES_REVIEWED U.S. News </DescField><DescField fid="ipcns">ONEW </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">US</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Police Shooting of Unarmed Black Man Roils Sacramento; Civil-rights leaders join family in calling for charges and protesters pledge to continue demonstrations</Para></Headline></Title><Corrections fid="cx"><Para>Corrections &amp; Amplifications</Para><Para>Benjamin Crump is an attorney for Stephon Clark's family. An earlier version of this article incorrectly spelled his name. (March 26, 2018)</Para></Corrections><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>The fatal police shooting of an unarmed black man in Sacramento, Calif., a week ago is renewing scrutiny on police killings, an issue that had faded over the past year as gun violence and the #MeToo movement seized the national spotlight.</Para><Para>Protesters have pledged to hold more demonstrations in the city against the shooting, while civil-rights leaders joined the family on Monday in calling for charges to be filed against two officers.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Stephon Clark, 22, was killed on Sunday, March 18, when police said he approached officers with his hands extended and holding an object that they believed to be a gun. But police said they found only a cellphone after they fired the fatal shots. Police had been called to the area that night because of reports of car break-ins, they said.</Para><Para>The person "who committed a mass shooting in Florida was not shot once, but a young black man holding a cellphone is shot 20 times," said Benjamin Crump, an attorney for Mr. Clark's family, at a news conference Monday, referring to the shooting at a Parkland, Fla., high school last month. Mr. Crump also represented the family of Michael Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old who was shot and killed in 2014 by a Ferguson, Mo., police officer. â€‹</Para><Para>Mr. Clark's grandmother Sequita Thompson recounted through tears how Sacramento police killed her grandson in her backyard a week ago. "They didn't have to kill him like that," said Ms. Thompson. "My great grandbabies don't have their daddy." Mr. Clark was a father of two.</Para><Para>Protests over the case have put a focus once again on police, which had in recent years faced waves of protests over shootings of unarmed black men. Demonstrators marched in Sacramento for several days last week, and also held a vigil, and organizers said they would take to the streets again this week. The protests so far have largely been peaceful.</Para><Para>The shooting has also drawn attention from athletes. On Sunday, players from the Sacramento Kings and Boston Celtics wore black shirts emblazoned with Mr. Clark's name before their game. NBA star and former Sacramento Kings player DeMarcus Cousins offered to pay for Mr. Clark's funeral.</Para><Para>Sacramento police last week released body-camera footage of the brief encounter, which shows officers following the man through a yard and shouting for him to stop and to show them his hands, before yelling "Gun, gun, gun!"</Para><Para>The union representing Sacramento police officers defended the two officers, whom police have yet to identify. "Even as tragic as this event is, we cannot ignore the fact that the shooting was legally justified under the law, within police policy, and in accordance with training," said Timothy Davis, president of the Sacramento Police Officers Association.</Para><Para>Sacramento Mayor Darrell Steinberg said last week he wouldn't draw any conclusions until the city's probe into the shooting is completed.</Para><Para>"Based on the videos alone, I cannot second guess the split-second decisions of our officers and I'm not going to do that," said Mr. Steinberg, a Democrat.</Para><Para>Mr. Steinberg also said questions raised by community members such as why police officers didn't immediately render first aid to Mr. Clark must be answered.</Para><Para>After nationwide protests over police shootings erupted in 2014 following Mr. Brown's death, police across the country revamped training and purchased body cameras in an effort to cut down on shootings and increase transparency.</Para><Para>Write to Zusha Elinson at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:zusha.elinson@wsj.com">zusha.elinson@wsj.com</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Zusha Elinson </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/police-shooting-of-unarmed-black-man-roils-sacramento-1522106069" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

